Below is a **complete, self‑contained binding** that can be dropped into an OCaml project and compiled with the usual
`ocamlc/ocamlopt` tool‑chain (the C side is compiled as C++, of course).  
It contains:

* **`pcapng.mli`** – the public OCaml interface (the only file a user of the library
  needs to open).
* **`pcapng.c`** – the C‑stub file (compiled as C++).  It implements the
  low‑level glue to the C++ `libpcapng` iterator and exposes three external
  functions that the `.ml` file (generated automatically by the compiler) will
  bind to.

The design goal is **maximum speed** for the hot per‑frame callback while still
being safe for the OCaml garbage collector and giving a pleasant OCaml API.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 1.  `pcapng.mli` – public OCaml interface
```ocaml
(* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   OCaml bindings for libpcapng – a high‑performance iterator over frames.
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- *)

(** Opaque handle to an opened pcapng collection. *)
type t

(** A single captured frame.
    - [timestamp] is the packet capture time, in nanoseconds since the epoch.
    - [data] is the raw packet bytes. *)
type frame = {
  timestamp : int64 ;
  data      : bytes ;
}

(** Open a pcapng file for reading.  Raises [Sys_error] if the file cannot be
    opened or is not a valid pcapng file. *)
val open_file : string -> t

(** Close a previously opened file.  After this call the handle must no longer
    be used.  It is also safe to rely on the finaliser that will automatically
    close the file when the OCaml value is collected. *)
val close : t -> unit

(** Iterate over all frames in the collection, calling [f] for each frame.
    The callback is executed **inside the C++ loop**, so the overhead per
    frame is only the cost of a single OCaml callback.  If [f] raises an
    exception the iteration stops and the exception is propagated to the
    caller. *)
val iter : t -> (frame -> unit) -> unit

(** Same as [iter] but any exception raised by the callback is caught and
    transformed into a call to [Printexc.print_backtrace] before being
    re‑raised.  This version is useful when you want a guaranteed back‑trace
    for debugging huge runs. *)
val iter_exn : t -> (frame -> unit) -> unit
```

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 2.  `pcapng.c` – C stub (compiled as C++)
> **NOTE** – The file must be compiled with a C++ compiler (`g++`/`clang++`)
> because it links against the C++ `libpcapng` API.  The exported symbols are
> declared `extern "C"` so that OCaml can find them.

```c
/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   C stub for OCaml bindings to libpcapng.
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */

#define CAML_NAME_SPACE               /* avoid name clashes */
#include <caml/mlvalues.h>
#include <caml/memory.h>
#include <caml/alloc.h>
#include <caml/custom.h>
#include <caml/callback.h>
#include <caml/fail.h>
#include <caml/bigarray.h>

#include <string>
#include <cstdint>
#include <exception>

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   The (fictional) libpcapng C++ API we are binding to.
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
namespace pcapng {

struct Frame {
    uint64_t timestamp_ns;          // nanoseconds since epoch
    const uint8_t* data;            // pointer to packet bytes (valid until next frame)
    size_t length;                  // length of the packet
};

class File {
public:
    explicit File(const std::string& path);
    ~File();

    // Return true while there are more frames; false when the iterator is exhausted.
    bool next(Frame& out);
    // Reset iterator to the beginning (not used by the binding but useful for tests).
    void rewind();
};

} // namespace pcapng

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   OCaml custom block that holds a pointer to a pcapng::File.
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
typedef struct {
    pcapng::File *file;   // owned by the block – freed by the finaliser
} caml_pcapng_handle;

/* Finaliser – called when the OCaml value is GC‑collected. */
static void caml_pcapng_finalize(value v) {
    caml_pcapng_handle *h = (caml_pcapng_handle *)Data_custom_val(v);
    if (h->file) {
        delete h->file;
        h->file = nullptr;
    }
}

/* Custom operations table – only a finaliser is needed. */
static struct custom_operations pcapng_ops = {
    "pcapng_file",
    caml_pcapng_finalize,
    custom_compare_default,
    custom_hash_default,
    custom_serialize_default,
    custom_deserialize_default,
    custom_compare_ext_default,
    custom_fixed_length_default
};

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   Helper: allocate a fresh custom block that owns a new pcapng::File.
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
static value caml_pcapng_wrap_file(pcapng::File *f) {
    CAMLparam0();
    CAMLlocal1(v);
    v = caml_alloc_custom(&pcapng_ops, sizeof(caml_pcapng_handle), 0, 1);
    ((caml_pcapng_handle *)Data_custom_val(v))->file = f;
    CAMLreturn(v);
}

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   Externally visible functions – declared "C" for OCaml linking.
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
extern "C" {

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   open_file : string -> t
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
CAMLprim value caml_pcapng_open_file(value v_path) {
    CAMLparam1(v_path);
    const char *c_path = String_val(v_path);
    try {
        pcapng::File *f = new pcapng::File(std::string(c_path));
        CAMLreturn(caml_pcapng_wrap_file(f));
    } catch (const std::exception &e) {
        caml_failwith(e.what());
    }
}

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   close : t -> unit
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
CAMLprim value caml_pcapng_close(value v_handle) {
    CAMLparam1(v_handle);
    caml_pcapng_handle *h = (caml_pcapng_handle *)Data_custom_val(v_handle);
    if (h->file) {
        delete h->file;
        h->file = nullptr;
    }
    CAMLreturn(Val_unit);
}

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   iter : t -> (frame -> unit) -> unit
   Calls the OCaml callback for every frame.  If the callback raises,
   the iteration stops and the exception propagates.
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
CAMLprim value caml_pcapng_iter(value v_handle, value v_cb) {
    CAMLparam2(v_handle, v_cb);
    CAMLlocal1(v_frame);          // the OCaml frame record we allocate each iteration

    caml_pcapng_handle *h = (caml_pcapng_handle *)Data_custom_val(v_handle);
    if (!h->file) caml_failwith("pcapng: file already closed");

    pcapng::File *file = h->file;
    pcapng::Frame cpp_frame;

    while (file->next(cpp_frame)) {
        /* Build OCaml record { timestamp; data } */
        v_frame = caml_alloc(2, 0);                 // record tag = 0, 2 fields
        Store_field(v_frame, 0, caml_copy_int64((int64_t)cpp_frame.timestamp_ns));

        /* Create a fresh OCaml bytes value for the packet payload */
        value v_bytes = caml_alloc_initialized_string(cpp_frame.length);
        memcpy(String_val(v_bytes), cpp_frame.data, cpp_frame.length);
        Store_field(v_frame, 1, v_bytes);

        /* Call the user supplied callback */
        caml_callback(v_cb, v_frame);
        /* If the callback raises, caml_callback propagates the exception,
           aborting the loop automatically. */
    }
    CAMLreturn(Val_unit);
}

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   iter_exn : t -> (frame -> unit) -> unit
   Same as iter, but catches any exception, prints a back‑trace and re‑raises.
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
CAMLprim value caml_pcapng_iter_exn(value v_handle, value v_cb) {
    CAMLparam2(v_handle, v_cb);
    CAMLlocal1(v_exn);

    caml_try {
        caml_pcapng_iter(v_handle, v_cb);
    } caml_catch {
        v_exn = caml_raise_exception(caml_current_exception());
        /* Print a back‑trace before re‑raising – helpful for huge runs. */
        caml_callback(*caml_named_value("Printexc.print_backtrace"), v_exn);
        caml_raise(v_exn);
    }
    CAMLreturn(Val_unit);
}

} /* extern "C" */
```

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 3.  How to compile & link

```bash
# 1. Compile the C stub (as C++) ------------------------------------------------
ocamlc -c -ccopt -std=c++17 pcapng.c   # produces pcapng.o (linked with libpcapng)

# 2. Compile the interface -------------------------------------------------------
ocamlc -c pcapng.mli                  # produces pcapng.cmi

# 3. Build a native library (optional) -----------------------------------------
ocamlopt -output-obj -o pcapng.o pcapng.c

# 4. Link everything together (example program `test.ml`) ----------------------
ocamlopt -o test \
    -cclib -lpcapng   \
    pcapng.cmx test.ml
```

Replace `-lpcapng` with the actual library name/paths required by your system.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 4.  Usage example (OCaml)

```ocaml
let () =
  let file = Pcapng.open_file "huge_capture.pcapng" in
  (* Count packets that are larger than 1500 bytes *)
  let big = ref 0 in
  Pcapng.iter file (fun frame ->
      if Bytes.length frame.Pcapng.data > 1500 then incr big
    );
  Printf.printf "Huge packets: %d\n%!" !big;
  Pcapng.close file
```

The hot path is the `while (file->next(...))` loop in `caml_pcapng_iter`.  
Only three OCaml allocations happen per frame (`frame` record + `bytes` value) and a
single `caml_callback` call, which is the fastest pattern achievable with the
standard OCaml C‑API.  The finaliser guarantees that native resources are
released even if the user forgets to call `close`.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 5.  Why this design is fast

| Design aspect                               | Reason it is fast / safe                                   |
|--------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------|
| **Iterates in C++**                         | No OCaml‑level loop overhead; the iterator runs in native code. |
| **Single `caml_callback` per frame**        | Minimal crossing cost – the only OCaml‑side work is the user callback. |
| **Custom block with finaliser**             | No extra reference counting; the native `File*` is reclaimed automatically. |
| **Raw `bytes` for packet data**              | No conversion to a list or string; `bytes` is a mutable, heap‑allocated buffer that can be handed to C code later if needed. |
| **Exception handling via `caml_callback`** | Propagation is automatic; `iter_exn` adds a back‑trace without extra per‑frame cost. |
| **No intermediate OCaml list**              | Avoids O(N) allocation of a huge list; memory usage stays constant. |

With the above binding the per‑frame overhead is essentially the cost of:

* allocating a tiny 2‑field record,
* copying the packet bytes (a `memcpy` of `frame.length` bytes), and
* performing a single OCaml callback.

That is the usual “best‑possible” cost for a hot callback in OCaml.
